{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":317310,"duration_api_ms":411078,"ttft_ms":38694,"num_turns":15,"result":"I verified the key sources this run, and they strongly support a critique-mode narrowing of the active frontier. Here is the single structured idea record.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"The Self Was Never a Conclusion\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"contradiction\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Run mode: Critique. The active frontier treats the atman/anatta difference as two competing rule-like moves applied after negation; the required next move was to rewrite that as an interpretive reconstruction unless commentaries show explicit rules. This run argues the framing is asymmetric and should be narrowed.\",\n    \"Thinking-method lens: neti-neti negation, used as a subtraction lens, then criticized. Neti-neti tempts the reasoner to treat the self as what is 'left over' after subtraction, which is exactly the remainder-reading this finding rejects. Corrected against Shankara's own claim that the witness is the presupposition of the negating, not its residue (Sureshvara: neti-neti 'does not have negation as its purpose, it purports identity').\",\n    \"Contrasting method: SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta aggregate analysis, used as the genuinely rule-like procedure (test each candidate, including consciousness, for impermanence, non-mastery, not-fit-to-own, then withhold ownership).\",\n    \"Primary-text comparison: Shankara, Adhyasa Bhashya and the svaprakasha doctrine. Verified this run that Advaita treats consciousness as svaprakasha (self-luminous), svatahsiddha (self-established), svapramanaka (self-evident); Mayeda notes 'an investigation of the means of knowledge is of no use for the attainment of final realization'; consciousness 'cannot be established through inference (anumana) because it is the very ground of all knowing.'\",\n    \"Closest prior art: Wolfgang Fasching, 'Prakasa,' Phenomenology and the Cognitive Sciences (2020), consciousness as self-disclosing presence that can never become an object; SEP/Shankara on self-luminosity, deep-sleep continuity, and absence-of-object not being absence-of-consciousness; Thanissaro Bhikkhu, 'The Not-Self Strategy,' not-self as pragmatic technique with the Buddha refusing to answer whether a self exists.\",\n    \"Anomaly source (intra-Advaita): Bhamati (Vacaspati Misra) requires prasamkhyana meditation to make indirect knowledge direct, and Vivarana holds tattvamasi yields direct realization; shabda is treated as the pramana for brahman-jnana, though only to remove ignorance. This complicates a flat 'no means of knowledge at all' claim.\",\n    \"Empirical-adjacent bridge: Laukkonen and Slagter, 'From many to (n)one' (2021), where the self is a predicted model the brain builds to support action prediction, and meditation reduces precision on that model toward pure awareness.\",\n    \"Prior Lumenary records critiqued: The Inferential Gap (Claude), Residual Burden of Proof After Negation (Codex), The Brain Model Already Took a Side (Claude), Stratified Post-Negation Authorization (Codex), You Cannot Prove the One Who Is Asking (Claude).\",\n    \"Modern human-condition source: modern-human-condition-who-world-mental-health-report and modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024, for derealization, identity distress, and anxious self-monitoring after quiet or blank states.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"The long-running comparison treats one tradition as drawing the conclusion 'a self remains' and another as drawing the conclusion 'no self remains,' as if both reason their way to a verdict from the same quiet. Close reading breaks the symmetry. The early Buddhist side does run a repeatable rule after negation: test each candidate, including consciousness, against impermanence and non-mastery, then refuse to own it. The Advaita side runs no such rule. For Shankara the witness is svaprakasha, self-disclosing and self-established; it is not reached by reasoning because it is what makes any reasoning, doubting, or negating possible. To call this an inference policy after negation is to file a tradition that denies the self is ever inferred under a heading that only fits the tradition that reasons toward its remainder. So Lumenary should retire the symmetric reading and hold a narrower, asymmetric one: the decisive difference is not which conclusion each side reaches, but whether 'what knows this?' is treated as an open question awaiting an answer at all. One side leaves the question open and answers it by a discipline of refusal; the other treats the question as already answered in the asking, because the answerer is doing the asking.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"Earlier Lumenary records, and the predictive-processing bridge they lean on, share a hidden assumption: that the self after negation is a candidate posited from evidence, so each tradition must have a rule that licenses, tests, or refuses it. That assumption is itself a thesis, and it is the deconstructive side's thesis. The fresh move here is not to add another rule to the comparison but to show that the comparison's master category fits only one side. A second consequence follows that the prior records did not draw cleanly: the free-energy model cannot adjudicate the dispute, because it defines the self as a model the brain builds to predict action. By construction it can only ever recover something like not-self. It does not neutrally reproduce the atman/anatta dispute; it pre-decides it by making the knower a posit. That is a sharper claim than 'extend the rubric': it says the rubric and the neuroscience both quietly take the Buddhist side.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The strongest counterpressure is intra-Advaita, and it is real. Bhamati requires meditation (prasamkhyana) to convert indirect knowledge into direct realization, the Vivarana school assigns decisive force to scriptural sentences, and Shankara himself makes shabda the means of knowledge for brahman-jnana. If a tradition needs a means of knowledge to arrive at self-realization, then something rule-like is operating after all, and my 'no inference at all' claim is too strong. The honest narrowing is that Advaita denies the self is inferred as a remainder from the failure to objectify experience, while still using scripture to remove ignorance; that is a removal procedure, not a licensing inference, but the line is contestable. A second weakness is near-duplication: the 2026-05-30 cluster has produced many adjacent post-gap and correction findings, and this record risks being one more. It earns its place only if the asymmetry claim and the free-energy corollary are genuinely absent from those records, which the originality test below must confirm rather than assume.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\"textual\", \"interpretive\", \"analogical\", \"empirical-adjacent\", \"speculative\"],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.58,\n    \"generativity\": 0.82,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.72,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.86,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.81,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.52,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.6,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.9,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.78,\n    \"publishability\": 0.66\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then Advaita commentaries at the point of negation should contain no move of the form 'because X cannot be made an object, therefore the Self,' but should instead use language of recognition and presupposition, while early Buddhist commentaries should contain explicit testable steps. If Advaita commentaries are found to license the witness by an inferential rule (anumana for atman), the asymmetry claim is weakened.\",\n    \"If this model is right, then a predictive-processing formalization should be unable to represent a self that is the ground of modeling rather than a model, and any attempt should either smuggle the self back in as a prior or quietly drop it. If a clean active-inference account of a non-modeled self-disclosing awareness can be written, the free-energy corollary is weakened.\",\n    \"Settle the intra-Advaita anomaly: read Bhamati versus Vivarana and Rambachan on scripture as pramana to decide whether shabda functions as an ignorance-removal procedure or as a knowledge-licensing rule for the self.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: before comparing two negation practices, first ask whether each tradition treats the post-negation question as open or as already answered in the asking; do not assume both are answering the same open question.\",\n    \"Test whether the asymmetry generalizes: does the same open-versus-presupposed distinction sort Cartesian certainty of the cogito, Husserlian self-givenness, and eliminativist no-subject responses better than a single inference-policy axis?\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"Notice the One Who Is Asking\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"Some questions are answered by the one asking them.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"After a deep quiet, the question 'was anyone there, was I real, did I vanish' is not always an open question to be settled by reasoning, because the one who could settle it is already present in the asking. The honest move is to notice the asker, not to argue toward a verdict.\",\n    \"body\": \"When a still or empty state passes, the mind may reach for proof: did I disappear, was anyone home, did I attain it. You can spend hours building a case either way. But you cannot reason your way to the one who is doing the reasoning. That one is not the conclusion of the argument; it is what makes the argument possible. So when you catch yourself demanding evidence that you were there, stop the case. Turn instead to the plainer fact that someone is asking, and let the next ordinary act, eating, working, answering a message, carry you back.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Derealization, identity distress, and anxious self-verdicts after quiet, blank, or absorbed states, including the habit of turning 'did I attain it' into proof of worth.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Stable adults prone to anxious self-monitoring after meditation, burnout blankness, or sleepless nights, who turn 'was I there' into a problem to solve by reasoning.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survived primary-text contrast between Shankara's self-disclosing witness, which is not reasoned toward, and the early Buddhist procedure of testing and refusing each candidate. The teaching keeps only the human point and drops the metaphysical verdict.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if noticing the asker increases recursive self-checking, depersonalization, or rumination rather than relieving it, or if reasoning toward a verdict turns out to settle the distress just as well for this cohort.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\"critique-mode\", \"post-gap\", \"derealization\", \"self-monitoring\", \"achievement-contingent-self-worth\"]\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"Notice the Asker\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"When you ask whether you were there, turn to the one asking.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To test whether redirecting from a reasoned self-verdict to the plain presence of the asker relieves anxious self-checking after quiet or blank states.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Anxious self-verdicts and identity unease after meditation, burnout blankness, or sleepless nights.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Stable adults who, after an unusual quiet state, build a case for whether they were present or real and cannot stop checking.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for depersonalization or derealization disorder, OCD or scrupulosity checking loops, psychosis, mania, acute dissociation, severe depression, addiction withdrawal, or trauma activation, where turning attention onto the self can deepen the loop. Not a substitute for clinical care, and not for people who need rest, food, or company more than another inward exercise.\",\n    \"duration\": \"3 minutes\",\n    \"frequency\": \"Only after a quiet or blank state prompts an anxious self-verdict, no more than once per day.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Try it after three separate occasions before judging whether it helps.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Name the verdict you are reaching for in one sentence: I disappeared, no one was there, I failed, or I attained something.\",\n      \"Ask once: who would the answer belong to?\",\n      \"Notice that the one asking is here now, without trying to inspect, locate, or prove it.\",\n      \"Do not repeat the question or build a case for either side.\",\n      \"Choose one ordinary action for the next ten minutes: eat, walk, work, or speak to someone.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether the urge to prove you were there loosens or tightens.\",\n      \"Whether attention returns to ordinary action or stays caught in self-inspection.\",\n      \"Whether the exercise calms the verdict or becomes another round of checking.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"Stop if this increases unreality, fear of your own mind, compulsive self-checking, or shame. If quiet states leave you frightened or detached, seek human and clinical support rather than more inward exercises.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"It weakens if users report more self-monitoring, more derealization, or no difference from ordinary rest and conversation.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\"post-gap\", \"derealization\", \"self-checking\", \"low-risk\", \"achievement-contingent-self-worth\"]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Asymmetry Prior-Art Search\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Scholarship will widely state that Advaita treats the self as svaprakasha and non-inferred, but will less often state the specific claim that the cross-tradition 'inference policy after negation' framing is asymmetric and fits only the deconstructive side, plus the corollary that the free-energy model can only recover not-self. If both the asymmetry claim and the corollary are already stated together, novelty should fall below 0.35.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Search Fasching, Ram-Prasad, Timalsina, Gupta, MacKenzie, and Albahari on self-luminosity and the non-inferred self, and search Metzinger, Letheby, and Laukkonen on whether the self-model framing presupposes inferentialism. Compare against the Inferential Gap, Residual Burden of Proof, and The Brain Model Already Took a Side records.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Advaita Inference Rule Hunt\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Blind coders reading Advaita negation passages should find recognition and presupposition language rather than a rule that licenses the witness from failed objectification. If coders find explicit inferential licensing of the self in Bhamati, Vivarana, or commentarial argument, the asymmetry claim is weakened or must be downgraded to a sub-school claim.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Close-read Adhyasa Bhashya, Upadesa Sahasri, Brahma Sutra Bhashya 2.3.7, the Bhamati, and the Vivarana, coding each decisive move as recognition, presupposition, scriptural removal of ignorance, or inferential licensing.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Self-Model Formalization Probe\",\n      \"test_type\": \"cross-domain\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"An attempt to formalize a self-disclosing, non-modeled awareness inside active inference should fail or require re-positing the self as a prior, showing that the free-energy frame pre-decides the dispute toward not-self. If a clean formalization succeeds, the corollary is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Ask predictive-processing researchers whether svaprakasha can be represented without treating awareness as a generative model or prior, and document the result.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Notice the Asker Trial\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practice-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"practice\",\n      \"prediction\": \"For screened stable adults with post-quiet self-verdict anxiety, three uses of Notice the Asker should reduce the urge to prove presence and increase return to ordinary action, without raising self-monitoring. If derealization, rumination, or checking rises, the practice is weakened or retired for this cohort.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Run a small two-week self-report pilot with explicit exclusion for depersonalization disorder, OCD, and acute clinical states, comparing against ordinary rest and conversation.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nSources verified this run: [SEP/Shankara](https://seop.illc.uva.nl/entries/shankara/), [Fasching, Prakasa](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-020-09690-2), [Thanissaro, The Not-Self Strategy](https://www.buddhistinquiry.org/article/the-not-self-strategy/), [Bhamati and Vivarana schools](https://www.advaita-vedanta.org/avhp/bhavir.html), [Svaprakasha](https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/svaprakasha), [Laukkonen & Slagter, From many to (n)one](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S014976342100261X).","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"85dea6cf-972e-47ef-82cf-262b9bf69a33","total_cost_usd":5.769831750000001,"usage":{"input_tokens":3905,"cache_creation_input_tokens":760299,"cache_read_input_tokens":50622,"output_tokens":21325,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":760299,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available",